# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sigfox
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The field has evolved due to the convergence of multiple technologies, including ubiquitous computing, sensors, embedded systems, and machine learning.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Traditional fields of embedded systems, wireless sensor networks, control systems, and automation independently and collectively enable the Internet of things.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] While in the consumer market, IoT technology is most commonly as smart home products—including devices and appliances like thermostats and smart speakers—the technology's largest applications are in the business and industrial sectors.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Commercial asset tracking and fleet management represent the largest single application of IoT, accounting for 22% of the total market, driven by the need to monitor mobile assets like vehicles and shipping containers.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The largest asset tracking sub-segments in transport & logistics are trailer and intermodal container tracking, reaching 5.8 million and 5.3 million active devices globally at the end of 2024 respectively.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Other major applications include industrial monitoring, smart metering in utilities, and connected healthcare.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Due to their interconnected nature, IoT devices are vulnerable to security breaches and privacy concerns.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] At the same time, the way these devices communicate wirelessly creates regulatory ambiguities, complicating jurisdictional boundaries of the data transfer.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Around 1972, for its remote site use, the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory developed a computer-controlled vending machine, adapted from a machine rented from Canteen Vending, which sold for cash or, through a computer terminal (Teletype Model 33 KSR), on credit.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Amongst its products were beer, yogurt, and milk.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] It was named *Prancing Pony*, after the name of the room, which was named after an inn in J.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Tolkien's epic fantasy novel The Lord of the Rings.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] A successor version still operates in the Computer Science Department at Stanford, with updated hardware and software.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] While it was initially accessible only on the CMU campus, it gained prominence as the first ARPANET-connected appliance.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Mark Weiser's 1991 paper on ubiquitous computing, "The Computer of the 21st Century", as well as academic venues such as UbiComp and PerCom, produced the contemporary vision of the IoT.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The field gained momentum when Bill Joy envisioned device-to-device communication as part of his "Six Webs" framework, which was presented at the World Economic Forum in Davos in 1999.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The concept of the "Internet of things" and the term itself first appeared in a speech by Peter T.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Lewis to the Congressional Black Caucus Foundation 15th Annual Legislative Weekend in Washington, D.C., published in September 1985.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The primary defining characteristic of the Internet of things has been considered its ability to embed short-range mobile transceivers in various gadgets and daily necessities, enabling new forms of communication between people and things, as well as between things themselves.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Defining the Internet of things as "simply the point in time when more 'things or objects' were connected to the Internet than people", Cisco Systems estimated that the IoT was "born" between 2008 and 2009, with the things/people ratio growing from 0.08 in 2003 to 1.84 in 2010.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The extensive set of applications for IoT devices is often divided into consumer, commercial, industrial, and infrastructure spaces.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] A growing portion of IoT devices is created for consumer use, including connected vehicles, home automation, wearable technology, connected health, and appliances with remote monitoring capabilities.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are part of the broader concept of home automation, which generally includes lighting, heating and air conditioning, media and security systems, and camera systems.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, long-term benefits could include energy savings by automatically ensuring lights and electronics are turned off or by making the residents in the home aware of usage.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] A smart home, also known as an automated home, could be based on a platform or hubs that control smart devices and appliances.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] For instance, using Apple's HomeKit, manufacturers can have their home products and accessories controlled by an application in iOS devices such as the iPhone and the Apple Watch.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] This could be a dedicated app or iOS native applications such as Siri.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] This can be demonstrated in the case of Lenovo's Smart Home Essentials, which is a line of smart home devices that are controlled through Apple's Home app or Siri without the need for a Wi-Fi bridge.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] There are also dedicated smart home hubs that are offered as standalone platforms to connect different smart home products.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] These include the Amazon Echo, Google Home, Apple's HomePod, and Samsung's SmartThings Hub.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to the commercial systems, there are many non-proprietary, open source ecosystems, including Home Assistant, OpenHAB, and Domoticz.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] One key application of a smart home is to assist the elderly and individuals with disabilities.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] These home systems use assistive technology to accommodate an owner's specific disabilities.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Voice control can assist users with sight and mobility limitations while alert systems can be connected directly to cochlear implants worn by individuals with hearing impairments.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] They can also be equipped with additional safety features, including sensors that monitor for medical emergencies such as falls or seizures.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Smart home technology applied in this way can provide users with more freedom and a higher quality of life.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Enterprise IoT" refers to devices used in business and corporate settings.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Medical Things** (**IoMT**) is an application of the IoT for medical and health-related purposes, data collection and analysis for research, and monitoring.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The IoMT has been referenced as "Smart Healthcare", as the technology for creating a digitized healthcare system, connecting available medical resources and healthcare services.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to enable remote health monitoring and emergency notification systems.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] These health monitoring devices can range from blood pressure and heart rate monitors to advanced devices capable of monitoring specialized implants, such as pacemakers, Fitbit electronic wristbands, or advanced hearing aids.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Some hospitals have begun implementing "smart beds" that can detect when they are occupied and when a patient is attempting to get up.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] It can also adjust itself to ensure appropriate pressure and support are applied to the patient without the manual interaction of nurses.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Specialized sensors can also be equipped within living spaces to monitor the health and general well-being of senior citizens, while ensuring that proper treatment is administered and assisting people in regaining lost mobility via therapy as well.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors create a network of intelligent sensors that are able to collect, process, transfer, and analyze valuable information in different environments, such as connecting in-home monitoring devices to hospital-based systems.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Other consumer devices to encourage healthy living, such as connected scales or wearable heart monitors, are also a possibility with the IoT.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] End-to-end health monitoring IoT platforms are also available for antenatal and chronic patients, helping one manage health vitals and recurring medication requirements.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Advances in plastic and fabric electronics fabrication methods have enabled ultra-low-cost, use-and-throw IoMT sensors.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors, along with the required radio-frequency identification electronics, can be fabricated on paper or e-textiles for wireless powered disposable sensing devices.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Applications have been established for point-of-care medical diagnostics, where portability and low system complexity are considered essential.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] As of 2018, IoMT was being applied in the clinical laboratory industry.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoMT in the insurance industry provides access to better and new types of dynamic information.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] This includes sensor-based solutions such as biosensors, wearables, connected health devices, and mobile apps to track customer behavior.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] This can lead to more accurate underwriting and new pricing models.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The application of the IoT in healthcare plays a fundamental role in managing chronic diseases and in disease prevention and control.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Remote monitoring is made possible through the connection of wireless solutions.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The connectivity enables health practitioners to capture patients' data and apply algorithms in health data analysis.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can assist in the integration of communications, control, and information processing across various transportation systems.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Application of the IoT extends to all aspects of transportation systems (i.e., the vehicle, the infrastructure, and the driver or user).
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Dynamic interaction between these components of a transport system enables inter- and intra-vehicular communication, smart traffic control, smart parking, electronic toll collection systems, logistics and fleet management, vehicle control, safety, and road assistance.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicle security applications, IoT-connected GPS trackers can operate for months or years on internal batteries, using low-power wide-area network protocols such as LTE-M to transmit location data to owners via smartphone applications when unauthorized movement is detected.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicular communication systems, vehicle-to-everything communication (V2X), consists of three main components: vehicle-to-vehicle communication (V2V), vehicle-to-infrastructure communication (V2I), and vehicle-to-pedestrian communication (V2P).
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Eventually, V2X is the first step to autonomous driving and connected road infrastructure.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to monitor and control the mechanical, electrical, and electronic systems used in various types of buildings (e.g., public and private, industrial, institutions, or residential) in home automation and building automation systems.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Also known as IIoT, industrial IoT devices acquire and analyze data from connected equipment, operational technology (OT), locations, and people.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Combined with operational technology (OT) monitoring devices, IIoT helps regulate and monitor industrial systems.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, the same implementation can be carried out for automated record updates of asset placement in industrial storage units as the size of the assets can vary from a small screw to the whole motor spare part, and misplacement of such assets can cause a loss of manpower time and money.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can connect various manufacturing devices equipped with sensing, identification, processing, communication, actuation, and networking capabilities.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Network control and management of manufacturing equipment, asset and situation management, or manufacturing process control enable IoT to be utilized for industrial applications and smart manufacturing.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligent systems enable rapid manufacturing and optimization of new products and rapid response to product demands.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Digital control systems, which aim to automate process controls, operator tools, and service information systems, alongside optimizing plant safety and security, fall within the purview of the IIoT.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Furthermore, IoT can also be applied to asset management via predictive maintenance, statistical evaluation, and measurements to maximize reliability.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Industrial management systems can be integrated with smart grids, enabling energy optimization.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Measurements, automated controls, plant optimization, health and safety management, and other functions are provided by networked sensors.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to general manufacturing, IoT is also used for processes in the industrialization of construction.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] There are numerous IoT applications in farming such as collecting data on temperature, rainfall, humidity, wind speed, pest infestation, and soil content.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] This data can be used to automate farming techniques, make informed decisions to improve quality and quantity, minimize risk and waste, and reduce the effort required to manage crops.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] For example, farmers can now monitor soil temperature and moisture from afar and even apply IoT-acquired data to precision fertilization programs.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The overall goal is that data from sensors, coupled with the farmer's knowledge and intuition about his or her farm, can help increase farm productivity, and also help reduce costs.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In August 2018, Toyota Tsusho began a partnership with Microsoft to create fish farming tools using the Microsoft Azure application suite for IoT technologies related to water management.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Developed in part by researchers from Kindai University, the water pump mechanisms use artificial intelligence to count the number of fish on a conveyor belt, analyze the number of fish, and deduce the effectiveness of water flow from the data the fish provide.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The FarmBeats project from Microsoft Research that uses TV white space to connect farms is also a part of the Azure Marketplace now.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are in use to monitor the environments and systems of boats and yachts.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Many pleasure boats are left unattended for days in summer, and months in winter so such devices provide valuable early alerts of boat flooding, fire, and deep discharge of batteries.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Monitoring and controlling operations of sustainable urban and rural infrastructures like bridges, railway tracks and on- and offshore wind farms is a key application of the IoT.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT infrastructure can be used for monitoring any events or changes in structural conditions that can compromise safety and increase risk.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can benefit the construction industry by cost-saving, time reduction, better quality workday, paperless workflow and increase in productivity.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] It can help in making faster decisions and saving money in Real-Time Data Analytics.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] It can also be used for scheduling repair and maintenance activities efficiently, by coordinating tasks between different service providers and users of these facilities.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can also be used to control critical infrastructure, like bridges, to provide access to ships.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The usage of IoT devices for monitoring and operating infrastructure is likely to significantly improve incident management and emergency response coordination, and quality of service, up-times and reduce costs of operation in all infrastructure-related areas.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Even areas such as waste management can benefit.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] There are several planned or ongoing large-scale deployments of the IoT to enable better management of cities and systems.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] For example, Songdo, South Korea, the first fully equipped and wired smart city, is gradually being built, with approximately 70 percent of the business district completed as of June 2018.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] A sizeable portion of the city, the first of its kind, is planned to be wired and automated to operate with little or no human intervention.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In 2014, another application was undergoing a project in Santander, Spain.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] For this deployment, two approaches have been adopted.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] This city of 180,000 inhabitants has already seen 18,000 downloads of its city smartphone app.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The app is connected to 10,000 sensors that enable services like parking search and environmental monitoring.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, city context information is used in this deployment, aiming to benefit merchants through a spark deals mechanism based on city behavior that aims at maximizing the impact of each notification.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Other examples of large-scale deployments underway include the Sino-Singapore Guangzhou Knowledge City; work on improving air and water quality, reducing noise pollution, and increasing transportation efficiency in San Jose, California; and smart traffic management in western Singapore.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Using its RPMA (Random Phase Multiple Access) technology, San Diego–based Ingenu has built a nationwide public network for low-bandwidth data transmissions using the same unlicensed 2.4 gigahertz spectrum as Wi-Fi.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Ingenu's "Machine Network" covers more than a third of the US population across 35 major cities including San Diego and Dallas.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] French company, Sigfox, commenced building an Ultra Narrowband wireless data network in the San Francisco Bay Area in 2014, the first business to achieve such a deployment in the U.S.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] It subsequently announced it would set up a total of 4000 base stations to cover a total of 30 cities in the U.S. by the end of 2016, making it the largest IoT network coverage provider in the country thus far.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco also participates in smart cities projects.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco has deployed technologies for Smart Wi-Fi, Smart Safety & Security, Smart Lighting, Smart Parking, Smart Transports, Smart Bus Stops, Smart Kiosks, Remote Expert for Government Services (REGS) and Smart Education in the five km area in the city of Vijayawada, India.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of a large deployment is the one completed by New York Waterways in New York City to connect all the city's vessels and be able to monitor them live 24/7.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The network was designed and engineered by Fluidmesh Networks, a Chicago-based company developing wireless networks for critical applications.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The NYWW network is currently providing coverage on the Hudson River, East River, and Upper New York Bay.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] With the wireless network in place, NY Waterway is able to take control of its fleet and passengers in a way that was not previously possible.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] New applications can include security, energy and fleet management, digital signage, public Wi-Fi, paperless ticketing and others.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Significant numbers of energy-consuming devices (e.g., lamps, household appliances, motors, pumps, etc.) already integrate Internet connectivity, which can allow them to communicate with utilities not only to balance power generation but also helps optimize the energy consumption as a whole.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] These devices allow for remote control by users, or central management via a cloud-based interface, and enable functions like scheduling (e.g., remotely powering on or off heating systems, controlling ovens, changing lighting conditions etc.).
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The smart grid is a utility-side IoT application; systems gather and act on energy and power-related information to improve the efficiency of the production and distribution of electricity.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Using advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) Internet-connected devices, electric utilities not only collect data from end-users, but also manage distribution automation devices like transformers.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Environmental monitoring applications of the IoT typically use sensors to assist in environmental protection by monitoring air or water quality, atmospheric or soil conditions, and can even include areas like monitoring the movements of wildlife and their habitats.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Development of resource-constrained devices connected to the Internet also means that other applications like earthquake or tsunami early-warning systems can also be used by emergency services to provide more effective aid.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices in this application typically span a large geographic area and can also be mobile.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] It has been argued that the standardization that IoT brings to wireless sensing will revolutionize this area.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of integrating the IoT is the concept of a "living lab." Living labs integrate and combine research and innovation processes, establishing within a public-private-people-partnership.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Between 2006 and January 2024, there were over 440 living labs (though not all are currently active) that use the IoT to collaborate and share knowledge between stakeholders to co-create innovative and technological products.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] When companies intend to implement and develop IoT services for smart cities, they need to have economic incentives.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The US government plays a key role in smart city projects; changes in policies will help cities to implement the IoT, which provides effectiveness, efficiency, and accuracy of the resources that are being used.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The Internet of Military Things (IoMT) is the application of IoT technologies in the military domain for the purposes of reconnaissance, surveillance, and other combat-related objectives.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] It is heavily influenced by the future prospects of warfare in an urban environment and involves the use of sensors, munitions, vehicles, robots, human-wearable biometrics, and other smart technology that is relevant on the battlefield.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] One of the examples of IOT devices used in the military is the Xaver 1000 system.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The Xaver 1000 was developed by Israel's Camero Tech, which is the latest in the company's line of "through-wall imaging systems." The Xaver line uses millimeter wave (MMW) radar, or radar in the range of 30-300 gigahertz.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] It is equipped with an AI-based life target tracking system as well as its own 3D 'sense-through-the-wall' technology.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Battlefield Things** (**IoBT**) is a project initiated and executed by the U.S.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) that focuses on the basic science related to the IoT that enhances the capabilities of Army soldiers.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In 2017, ARL launched the Internet of Battlefield Things Collaborative Research Alliance (IoBT-CRA), establishing a working collaboration between industry, university, and Army researchers to advance the theoretical foundations of IoT technologies and their applications to Army operations.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The **Ocean of Things** project is a DARPA-led program designed to establish an Internet of things across large ocean areas for the purposes of collecting, monitoring, and analyzing environmental and vessel activity data.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The project entails the deployment of about 50,000 floats that house a passive sensor suite that autonomously detects and tracks military and commercial vessels as part of a cloud-based network.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] There are several applications of smart or active packaging in which a QR code or NFC tag is affixed to a product or its packaging.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The tag itself is passive; however, it contains a unique identifier (typically a URL) which enables a user to access digital content about the product via a smartphone.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Strictly speaking, such passive items are not part of the Internet of things, but they can be seen as enablers of digital interactions.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Internet of Packaging" has been coined to describe applications in which unique identifiers are used, to automate supply chains, and are scanned on large scale by consumers to access digital content.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Authentication of the unique identifiers, and thereby of the product itself, is possible via a copy-sensitive digital watermark or copy detection pattern for scanning when scanning a QR code, while NFC tags can encrypt communication.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of Things (IoT), As of April 2026, the number of devices connected and controlled via the Internet has increased.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Applications of IoT technology vary across devices, but many share common characteristics.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT creates opportunities for more direct integration of the physical world into computer-based systems, resulting in efficiency improvements, economic benefits, and reduced human exertions.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT Analytics reported there were 16.6 billion IoT devices connected in 2023.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In 2020, the same firm projected there would be 30 billion devices connected by 2025.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] As of October, 2024, there are around 17 billion.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control are not part of the original concept of the Internet of things.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control do not necessarily require Internet structures, either.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] However, there is a shift in research (by companies such as Intel) to integrate the concepts of the IoT and autonomous control, with initial outcomes towards this direction considering objects as the driving force for autonomous IoT.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] An approach in this context is deep reinforcement learning where most of IoT systems provide a dynamic and interactive environment.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Training an agent (i.e., IoT device) to behave smartly in such an environment cannot be addressed by conventional machine learning algorithms such as supervised learning.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Through a reinforcement learning approach, a learning agent can sense the environment's state (e.g., sensing home temperature), perform actions (e.g., turn HVAC on or off) and learn by maximizing accumulated rewards it receives.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligence can be offered at three levels: IoT devices, Edge/Fog nodes, and cloud computing.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The need for intelligent control and decision at each level depends on the time sensitiveness of the IoT application.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] For example, an autonomous vehicle's camera needs to make real-time obstacle detection to avoid an accident.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] This fast decision making would not be possible if it is necessary to transfer data from the vehicle to cloud instances and return the predictions back to the vehicle.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Instead, the operation should be performed locally in the vehicle.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Integrating advanced machine learning algorithms, including deep learning, into IoT devices is an active research area to make smart objects closer to reality.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, it is possible to get the most value out of IoT deployments through analyzing IoT data, extracting hidden information, and predicting control decisions.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] A wide variety of machine learning techniques have been used in IoT domain ranging from traditional methods such as regression, support vector machine, and random forest to advanced ones such as convolutional neural networks, LSTM, and variational autoencoder.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Modern IoT products and solutions in the marketplace use a variety of different technologies to support such context-aware automation, but more sophisticated forms of intelligence are requested to permit sensor units and intelligent cyber-physical systems to be deployed in real environments.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT system architecture, in its simplistic view, consists of three tiers: Tier 1: Devices, Tier 2: the Edge Gateway, and Tier 3: the Cloud.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Devices include networked things, such as the sensors and actuators found in IoT equipment, particularly those that use protocols such as Modbus, Bluetooth, Zigbee, or proprietary protocols, to connect to an Edge Gateway.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The Edge Gateway layer consists of sensor data aggregation systems called Edge Gateways that provide functionality, such as pre-processing of the data, securing connectivity to cloud, using systems such as WebSockets, the event hub, and, even in some cases, edge analytics or fog computing.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Edge Gateway layer is also required to give a common view of the devices to the upper layers to facilitate in easier management.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The final tier includes the cloud application built for IoT using the microservices architecture, which are usually polyglot and inherently secure in nature using HTTPS/OAuth.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] It includes various database systems that store sensor data, such as time series databases or asset stores using backend data storage systems (e.g.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The cloud tier in most cloud-based IoT system features event queuing and messaging system that handles communication that transpires in all tiers.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Some experts classified the three-tiers in the IoT system as edge, platform, and enterprise and these are connected by proximity network, access network, and service network, respectively.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT requires huge scalability in the network space to handle the surge of devices.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IETF 6LoWPAN can be used to connect devices to IP networks.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] With billions of devices being added to the Internet space, IPv6 may play an important role in handling the network layer scalability.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IETF's Constrained Application Protocol, ZeroMQ, and MQTT can provide lightweight data transport.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In practice, many groups of IoT devices are hidden behind gateway nodes and may not have unique addresses.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Also, the vision of everything being interconnected is not needed for most applications as it is mainly the data that needs interconnecting at a higher layer.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Fog computing is a viable alternative to prevent such a large burst of data flow through the Internet.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The edge devices' computation power to analyze and process data is extremely limited.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Limited processing power is a key attribute of IoT devices as their purpose is to supply data about physical objects while remaining autonomous.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Heavy processing requirements use more battery power, harming IoT's ability to operate.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Scalability is easy because IoT devices simply supply data through the Internet to a server with sufficient processing power.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Performance is improved, especially for huge IoT systems with millions of nodes.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Conventional IoT is connected via a mesh network and led by a major head node (centralized controller).
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The head node decides how a data is created, stored, and transmitted.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In contrast, decentralized IoT attempts to divide IoT systems into smaller divisions.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The head node authorizes partial decision-making power to lower level sub-nodes under mutual agreed policy.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Some approaches to decentralized IoT attempt to address the limited bandwidth and hashing capacity of battery-powered or wireless IoT devices via blockchain.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In semi-open or closed loops (i.e., value chains, whenever a global finality can be settled) the IoT is often analyzed as a complex system due to the large number of different interactions between autonomous actors, and its capacity to integrate new actors.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] At the overall stage (full open loop) it will likely be seen as a chaotic environment (since systems always have finality).
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] As a practical approach, not all elements on the Internet of things run in a global, public space.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Subsystems are often implemented to mitigate the risks of privacy, control and reliability.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] For example, domestic robotics (domotics) running inside a smart home might only share data within and be available via a local network.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Managing and controlling a high dynamic ad hoc IoT things/devices network is a complex task within traditional network architecture, software-defined networking (SDN) provides a dynamic approach that better fits the special requirements of IoT applications.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The exact scale of the Internet of things is unknown, with quotes of billions or trillions often quoted at the beginning of IoT articles.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In 2015, there were 83 million smart devices in people's homes.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] This number is expected to grow to 193 million devices by 2020.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In 2023, the number of connected IoT devices will reach 16.6 billion.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] The number of online-capable devices grew 31% from 2016 to 2017 to reach 8.4 billion.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of things, the precise geographic location of a thing—and also the precise geographic dimensions of a thing—can be critical.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] (Note that some things on the Internet of things will be sensors, and sensor location is usually important.) The GeoWeb and Digital Earth are applications that become possible when things can become organized and connected by location.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] However, the challenges that remain include the constraints of variable spatial scales, the need to handle massive amounts of data, and an indexing for fast search and neighbour operations.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] On the Internet of things, if things are able to take actions on their own initiative, this human-centric mediation role is eliminated.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Thus, the time-space context that we as humans take for granted must be given a central role in this information ecosystem.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Just as standards play a key role on the Internet and the Web, geo-spatial standards will play a key role on the Internet of things.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Many IoT devices have the potential to take a piece of this market.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] For improved user interaction, some technology leaders are joining forces to create standards for communication between devices to solve this problem.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Others are turning to the concept of predictive interaction of devices, "where collected data is used to predict and trigger actions on the specific devices" while making them work together.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Social Internet of things (SIoT) is a new kind of IoT that focuses on the importance of social interaction and relationships between IoT devices.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT defines a device with an identity like a citizen in a community and connects them to the Internet to provide services to its users.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT defines a social network for IoT devices only to interact with each other for different goals that to serve human.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is different from the original IoT in terms of the collaboration characteristics.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT is passive; it was set to serve for dedicated purposes with existing IoT devices in a predetermined system.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is active, it was programmed and managed by AI to serve for unplanned purposes with mix and match of potential IoT devices from different systems that benefit its users.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices with built-in sociability are able to broadcast their abilities or functionality, which can be used to discover and share information with other IoT devices in the same or nearby network, realizing SIoT.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Facilitating further functionality with these abilities could be helpful during emergencies.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] IoT sensors on the vehicles, road and traffic lights monitor the conditions of the vehicles and drivers and alert when attention is needed, and also coordinate themselves automatically to ensure autonomous driving is working normally.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] If a crash happens, the IoT camera will inform the nearest hospital and police station for help.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] System security is always a concern for any technology, and it is more crucial for SIoT as not only the security of oneself needs to be considered, but also the mutual trust mechanism between collaborative IoT devices from time to time, from place to place.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] Another critical challenge for SIoT is the accuracy and reliability of the sensors.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p01] In most circumstances, IoT sensors would need to respond quickly to avoid accidents, injury, and loss of life.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] There are many technologies that enable the IoT.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The original idea of the Auto-ID Center is based on RFID tags and distinct identification through the Electronic Product Code.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] This has evolved into objects having an IP address or URI.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] An alternative view, from the world of the Semantic Web focuses instead on making all things (not just those electronic, smart, or RFID-enabled) addressable by the existing naming protocols, such as URI.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The objects themselves do not converse, but they may now be referred to by other agents, such as powerful centralised servers acting for their human owners.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Integration with the Internet implies that devices will use an IP address as a distinct identifier.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Due to the limited address space of IPv4 (which allows for 4.3 billion different addresses), objects in the IoT will have to use the next generation of the Internet protocol (IPv6) to scale to the extremely large address space required.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Internet-of-things devices additionally will benefit from the stateless address auto-configuration present in IPv6, as it reduces the configuration overhead on the hosts, and the IETF 6LoWPAN header compression.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] To a large extent, the future of the Internet of things will not be possible without the support of IPv6; and consequently, the global adoption of IPv6 in the coming years will be critical for the successful development of the IoT in the future.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Different technologies have different roles in a protocol stack.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] This is a list of technical standards for the IoT, most of which are open standards, and the standards organizations that aspire to successfully setting them.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Some scholars and activists argue that the IoT can be used to create new models of civic engagement if device networks can be open to user control and interoperable platforms.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that political life in both democracies and authoritarian regimes will be shaped by the way the IoT will be used for civic engagement.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] For that to happen, he argues that any connected device should be able to divulge a list of the "ultimate beneficiaries" of its sensor data and that individual citizens should be able to add new organisations to the beneficiary list.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, he argues that civil society groups need to start developing their IoT strategy for making use of data and engaging with the public.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] One of the key drivers of the IoT is data.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The success of the idea of connecting devices to make them more efficient is dependent upon access to and storage & processing of data.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] For this purpose, companies working on the IoT collect data from multiple sources and store it in their cloud network for further processing.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] This leaves the door wide open for privacy and security dangers and single point vulnerability of multiple systems.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The other issues pertain to consumer choice and ownership of data and how it is used.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Though still in their infancy, regulations and governance regarding these issues of privacy, security, and data ownership continue to develop.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Some examples of legislation that is relevant to privacy and data collection are: the US Privacy Act of 1974, OECD Guidelines on the Protection of Privacy and Transborder Flows of Personal Data of 1980, and the EU Directive 95/46/EC of 1995.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] However, the FTC stopped at just making recommendations for now.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] A resolution passed by the Senate in March 2015, is already being considered by the Congress.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] This resolution recognized the need for formulating a National Policy on IoT and the matter of privacy, security and spectrum.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Approved on 28 September 2018, California Senate Bill No.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Several standards for the IoT industry are actually being established relating to automobiles because most concerns arising from use of connected cars apply to healthcare devices as well.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In fact, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) is preparing cybersecurity guidelines and a database of best practices to make automotive computer systems more secure.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] A recent report from the World Bank examines the challenges and opportunities in government adoption of IoT.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In early December 2021, the U.K. government introduced the Product Security and Telecommunications Infrastructure bill (PST), an effort to legislate IoT distributors, manufacturers, and importers to meet certain cybersecurity standards.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The bill also seeks to improve the security credentials of consumer IoT devices.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] For example, wireless connectivity for IoT devices can be done using Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, Wi-Fi HaLow, Zigbee, Z-Wave, LoRa, NB-IoT, Cat M1 as well as completely custom proprietary radios – each with its own advantages and disadvantages; and unique support ecosystem.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The IoT's amorphous computing nature is also a problem for security, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] One set of researchers says that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active Android devices vulnerable.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that the Internet of things offers immense potential for empowering citizens, making government transparent, and broadening information access.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Howard cautions, however, that privacy threats are enormous, as is the potential for social control and political manipulation.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Concerns about privacy have led many to consider the possibility that big data infrastructures such as the Internet of things and data mining are inherently incompatible with privacy.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Key challenges of increased digitalization in the water, transport or energy sector are related to privacy and cybersecurity which necessitate an adequate response from research and policymakers alike.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Writer Adam Greenfield claims that IoT technologies are not only an invasion of public space but are also being used to perpetuate normative behavior, citing an instance of billboards with hidden cameras that tracked the demographics of passersby who stopped to read the advertisement.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Council compared the increased prevalence of digital surveillance due to the Internet of things to the concept of the panopticon described by Jeremy Bentham in the 18th century.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The assertion is supported by the works of French philosophers Michel Foucault and Gilles Deleuze.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In *Discipline and Punish: The Birth of the Prison*, Foucault asserts that the panopticon was a central element of the discipline society developed during the Industrial Era.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Foucault also argued that the discipline systems established in factories and school reflected Bentham's vision of panopticism.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In his 1992 paper "Postscripts on the Societies of Control", Deleuze wrote that the discipline society had transitioned into a control society, with the computer replacing the panopticon as an instrument of discipline and control while still maintaining the qualities similar to that of panopticism.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Peter-Paul Verbeek, a professor of philosophy of technology at the University of Twente, Netherlands, writes that technology already influences our moral decision making, which in turn affects human agency, privacy and autonomy.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] He cautions against viewing technology merely as a human tool and advocates instead to consider it as an active agent.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Tim O'Reilly believes that the way companies sell IoT devices to consumers is misplaced, disputing the notion that the IoT is about gaining efficiency from putting all kinds of devices online and postulating that, "IoT is really about human augmentation.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Editorials at WIRED have also expressed concern, one stating, "What you're about to lose is your privacy.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) expressed concern regarding the ability of IoT to erode people's control over their own lives.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The ACLU wrote that "There's simply no way to forecast how these immense powers – disproportionately accumulating in the hands of corporations seeking financial advantage and governments craving ever more control – will be used.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In response to rising concerns about privacy and smart technology, in 2007, the British Government stated it would follow formal Privacy by Design principles when implementing its smart metering program.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The program would lead to the replacement of traditional power meters with smart power meters, which could track and manage energy usage more accurately.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] However the British Computer Society is doubtful these principles were ever actually implemented.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In 2009, the Dutch Parliament rejected a similar smart metering program, basing their decision on privacy concerns.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The Dutch program later revised and passed in 2011.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] A challenge for producers of IoT applications is to clean, process and interpret the vast amount of data that is gathered by the sensors.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] There is a solution proposed for the analytics of the information referred to as Wireless Sensor Networks.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] These networks share data among sensor nodes that are sent to a distributed system for the analytics of the sensory data.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Another challenge is the storage of this bulk data.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Depending on the application, there could be high data acquisition requirements, which in turn lead to high storage requirements.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In 2013, the Internet was estimated to be responsible for consuming 5% of the total energy produced, and a "daunting challenge to power" IoT devices to collect and even store data still remains.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Data silos, although a common challenge of legacy systems, still commonly occur with the implementation of IoT devices, particularly within manufacturing.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] As there are a lot of benefits to be gained from IoT and IIoT devices, the means in which the data is stored can present serious challenges without the principles of autonomy, transparency, and interoperability being considered.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The challenges do not occur by the device itself, but the means in which databases and data warehouses are set up.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] These challenges were identified by Keller (2021) when investigating the IT and application landscape of I4.0 implementation within German M&E manufacturers.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Security is the biggest concern in adopting Internet of things technology, with concerns that rapid development is happening without appropriate consideration of the profound security challenges involved and the regulatory changes that might be necessary.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The rapid development of the Internet of Things (IoT) has allowed billions of devices to connect to the network.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Due to too many connected devices and the limitation of communication security technology, various security issues gradually appear in the IoT.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Most of the technical security concerns are similar to those of conventional servers, workstations and smartphones.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] These concerns include using weak authentication, forgetting to change default credentials, unencrypted messages sent between devices, SQL injections, man-in-the-middle attacks, and poor handling of security updates.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] However, many IoT devices have severe operational limitations on the computational power available to them.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] These constraints often make them unable to directly use basic security measures such as implementing firewalls or using strong cryptosystems to encrypt their communications with other devices - and the low price and consumer focus of many devices makes a robust security patching system uncommon.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Rather than conventional security vulnerabilities, fault injection attacks are on the rise and targeting IoT devices.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] A fault injection attack is a physical attack on a device to purposefully introduce faults in the system to change the intended behavior.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Faults might happen unintentionally due to environmental noises and electromagnetic fields.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] There are ideas stemming from control-flow integrity (CFI) to prevent fault injection attacks and system recovery to a healthy state before the fault.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Computer-controlled devices in automobiles such as brakes, engine, locks, hood and trunk releases, horn, heat, and dashboard have been shown to be vulnerable to attackers who have access to the on-board network.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In some cases, vehicle computer systems are Internet-connected, allowing them to be exploited remotely.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] By 2008, security researchers had shown the ability to remotely control pacemakers without authority.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Later, hackers demonstrated remote control of insulin pumps and implantable cardioverter defibrillators.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Poorly secured Internet-accessible IoT devices can also be subverted to attack others.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In 2016, a distributed denial of service attack powered by Internet of things devices running the Mirai malware took down a DNS provider and major web sites.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had infected roughly 65,000 IoT devices within the first 20 hours.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Eventually, the infections increased to around 200,000 to 300,000 infections.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Brazil, Colombia and Vietnam made up of 41.5% of the infections.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had singled out specific IoT devices that consisted of DVRs, IP cameras, routers and printers.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] These sorts of attacks have caused security experts to view IoT as a real threat to Internet services.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] National Intelligence Council in an unclassified report maintains that it would be hard to deny "access to networks of sensors and remotely-controlled objects by enemies of the United States, criminals, and mischief makers...
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] An open market for aggregated sensor data could serve the interests of commerce and security no less than it helps criminals and spies identify vulnerable targets.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Thus, massively parallel sensor fusion may undermine social cohesion, if it proves to be fundamentally incompatible with Fourth-Amendment guarantees against unreasonable search." In general, the intelligence community views the Internet of things as a rich source of data.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] There have been a range of responses to concerns over security.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Security Foundation (IoTSF) was launched on 23 September 2015 with a mission to secure the Internet of things by promoting knowledge and best practices.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Its founding board is made up of technology providers and telecommunications companies.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, large IT companies are continually developing innovative solutions to ensure the security of IoT devices.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In 2017, Mozilla launched Project Things, which allows to route IoT devices through a safe Web of Things gateway.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] As per the estimates from KBV Research, the overall IoT security market would grow at 27.9% rate during 2016–2022 as a result of growing infrastructural concerns and diversified usage of Internet of things.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Governmental regulation is argued by some to be necessary to secure IoT devices and the wider Internet – as market incentives to secure IoT devices is insufficient.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] It was found that due to the nature of most of the IoT development boards, they generate predictable and weak keys which make it easy to be utilized by man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] However, various hardening approaches were proposed by many researchers to resolve the issue of SSH weak implementation and weak keys.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] IoT security within the field of manufacturing presents different challenges and varying perspectives.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Within the EU and Germany, data protection is constantly referenced throughout manufacturing and digital policy, particularly that of I4.0.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] However, the attitude towards data security differs from the enterprise perspective, whereas there is an emphasis on less data protection in the form of GDPR, as the data being collected from IoT devices in the manufacturing sector does not display personal details.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Yet, research has indicated that manufacturing experts are concerned about "data security for protecting machine technology from international competitors with the ever-greater push for interconnectivity".
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] IoT systems are typically controlled by event-driven smart apps that take as input either sensed data, user inputs, or other external triggers (from the Internet) and command one or more actuators towards providing different forms of automation.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of sensors include smoke detectors, motion sensors, and contact sensors.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of actuators include smart locks, smart power outlets, and door controls.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Popular control platforms on which third-party developers can build smart apps that interact wirelessly with these sensors and actuators include Samsung's SmartThings, Apple's HomeKit, and Amazon's Alexa, among others.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Detecting flaws that lead to such states, requires a holistic view of installed apps, component devices, their configurations, and more importantly, how they interact.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Recently, researchers from the University of California Riverside have proposed IotSan, a novel practical system that uses model checking as a building block to reveal "interaction-level" flaws by identifying events that can lead the system to unsafe states.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] They have evaluated IotSan on the Samsung SmartThings platform.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] From 76 manually configured systems, IotSan detects 147 vulnerabilities (i.e., violations of safe physical states/properties).
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Given widespread recognition of the evolving nature of the design and management of the Internet of things, sustainable and secure deployment of IoT solutions must design for "anarchic scalability".
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Application of the concept of anarchic scalability can be extended to physical systems (i.e. controlled real-world objects), by virtue of those systems being designed to account for uncertain management futures.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] This hard anarchic scalability thus provides a pathway forward to fully realize the potential of Internet-of-things solutions by selectively constraining physical systems to allow for all management regimes without risking physical failure.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Brown University computer scientist Michael Littman has argued that successful execution of the Internet of things requires consideration of the interface's usability as well as the technology itself.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] A concern regarding Internet-of-things technologies pertains to the environmental impacts of the manufacture, use, and eventual disposal of all these semiconductor-rich devices.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Modern electronics are replete with a wide variety of heavy metals and rare-earth metals, as well as highly toxic synthetic chemicals.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] This makes them extremely difficult to properly recycle.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Electronic components are often incinerated or placed in regular landfills.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Furthermore, the human and environmental cost of mining the rare-earth metals that are integral to modern electronic components continues to grow.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] This leads to societal questions concerning the environmental impacts of IoT devices over their lifetime.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The Electronic Frontier Foundation has raised concerns that companies can use the technologies necessary to support connected devices to intentionally disable or "brick" their customers' devices via a remote software update or by disabling a service necessary to the operation of the device.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In one example, home automation devices sold with the promise of a "Lifetime Subscription" were rendered useless after Nest Labs acquired Revolv and made the decision to shut down the central servers the Revolv devices had used to operate.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Owners should be free to point their devices to a different server or collaborate on improved software.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] But such action violates the United States DMCA section 1201, which only has an exemption for "local use".
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] This forces tinkerers who want to keep using their own equipment into a legal grey area.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] EFF thinks buyers should refuse electronics and software that prioritize the manufacturer's wishes above their own.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of post-sale manipulations include Google Nest Revolv, disabled privacy settings on Android, Sony disabling Linux on PlayStation 3, and enforced EULA on Wii U.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Kevin Lonergan at *Information Age*, a business technology magazine, has referred to the terms surrounding the IoT as a "terminology zoo".
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The lack of clear terminology is not "useful from a practical point of view" and a "source of confusion for the end user".
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] A company operating in the IoT space could be working in anything related to sensor technology, networking, embedded systems, or analytics.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Regarding IIoT, an industrial sub-field of IoT, the Industrial Internet Consortium's Vocabulary Task Group has created a "common and reusable vocabulary of terms" to ensure "consistent terminology" across publications issued by the Industrial Internet Consortium.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] IoT One has created an IoT Terms Database including a New Term Alert to be notified when a new term is published.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] As of March 2020, this database aggregates 807 IoT-related terms, while keeping material "transparent and comprehensive".
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Despite a shared belief in the potential of the IoT, industry leaders and consumers are facing barriers to adopting IoT technology more widely.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Mike Farley argued in Forbes that while IoT solutions appeal to early adopters, they either lack interoperability or a clear use case for end-users.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] A study by Ericsson regarding the adoption of IoT among Danish companies suggests that many struggle "to pinpoint exactly where the value of IoT lies for them".
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] As for IoT, especially in regard to consumer IoT, information about a user's daily routine is collected so that the "things" around the user can cooperate to provide better services that fulfill personal preferences.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] When the collected information which describes a user in detail travels through multiple hops in a network, due to a diverse integration of services, devices and network, the information stored on a device is vulnerable to privacy violation by compromising nodes existing in an IoT network.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] For example, on 21 October 2016, a multiple distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks systems operated by domain name system provider Dyn, which caused the inaccessibility of several websites, such as GitHub, Twitter, and others.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] This attack is executed through a botnet consisting of a large number of IoT devices including IP cameras, gateways, and even baby monitors.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Information privacy regulations also require organisations to practice "reasonable security".
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] As each organisation's environment is unique, it can prove challenging to demonstrate what "reasonable security" is and what potential risks could be involved for the business.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] According to antivirus provider Kaspersky, there were 639 million data breaches of IoT devices in 2020 and 1.5 billion breaches in the first six months of 2021.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] One method of overcoming the barrier of safety issues is the introduction of standards and certification of devices.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] In 2024, two voluntary and non-competing programs were proposed and launched in the United States: the US Cyber Trust Mark from The Federal Communications Commission and CSA's IoT Device Security Specification from the Connectivity Standards Alliance.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] The programs incorporate international expertise, with the CSA mark recognized by the Singapore Cybersecurity Agency.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Compliance means that IoT devices can resist hacking, control hijacking and theft of confidential data.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Some of these companies risk being "kodaked" – "Kodak was a market leader until digital disruption eclipsed film photography with digital photos" – failing to "see the disruptive forces affecting their industry" and "to truly embrace the new business models the disruptive change opens up".
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] According to a 2018 study, 70–75% of IoT deployments were stuck in the pilot or prototype stage, unable to reach scale due in part to a lack of business planning.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Even though scientists, engineers, and managers across the world are continuously working to create and exploit the benefits of IoT products, there are some flaws in the governance, management and implementation of such projects.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Despite tremendous forward momentum in the field of information and other underlying technologies, IoT still remains a complex area and the problem of how IoT projects are managed still needs to be addressed.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] IoT projects must be run differently than simple and traditional IT, manufacturing or construction projects.
[src:sigfox/internet-of-things-p02] Because IoT projects have longer project timelines, a lack of skilled resources and several security/legal issues, there is a need for new and specifically designed project processes.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The **ISM radio bands** are portions of the radio spectrum reserved internationally for *industrial, scientific and medical* (ISM) purposes, excluding applications in telecommunications.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Examples of applications for the use of radio frequency (RF) energy in these bands include RF heating, microwave ovens, and medical diathermy machines.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The powerful emissions of these devices can create electromagnetic interference and disrupt radio communication using the same frequency, so these devices are limited to certain bands of frequencies.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] In general, communications equipment operating in ISM bands must tolerate any interference generated by ISM applications, and users have no regulatory protection from ISM device operation in these bands.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Cordless phones, Bluetooth devices, near-field communication (NFC) devices, garage door openers, baby monitors, and wireless computer networks (Wi-Fi) may all use the ISM frequencies, although these low-power transmitters are not considered to be ISM devices.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The ISM bands are defined by the ITU Radio Regulations (article 5) in footnotes 5.138, 5.150, and 5.280 of the Radio Regulations.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Individual countries' use of the bands designated in these sections may differ due to variations in national radio regulations.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Because communication devices using the ISM bands must tolerate any interference from ISM equipment, unlicensed operations are typically permitted to use these bands, since unlicensed operation typically needs to be tolerant of interference from other devices anyway.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The ISM bands share allocations with unlicensed and licensed operations; however, due to the high likelihood of harmful interference, licensed use of the bands is typically low.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] In the United States, uses of the ISM bands are governed by Part 18 of the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) rules, while Part 15 contains the rules for unlicensed communication devices, even those that share ISM frequencies.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] In Europe, the ETSI develops standards for the use of short-range devices, some of which operate in ISM bands.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The use of the ISM bands is regulated by the national spectrum regulation authorities that are members of the CEPT.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The allocation of radio frequencies is provided according to *Article 5* of the ITU Radio Regulations (edition 2012).
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] In order to improve harmonisation in spectrum utilisation, the majority of service allocations stipulated in this document were incorporated in national tables of frequency allocations and utilisations which are within the responsibilities of the appropriate national administrations.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The allocation might be primary, secondary, exclusive, or shared.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Exclusive or shared utilization is within the responsibility of administrations.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] ITU RR, (Footnote 5.280) = In Germany, Austria, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, North Macedonia, Liechtenstein, Montenegro, Portugal, Serbia, Slovenia and Switzerland, the band 433.05–434.79 MHz (center frequency 433.92 MHz) is designated for *ISM applications*.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Radio communication services of these countries operating within this band must accept harmful interference which may be caused by these applications.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The ISM bands were first established at the International Telecommunications Conference of the ITU in Atlantic City, 1947.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The American delegation specifically proposed several bands, including the now commonplace 2.4 GHz band, to accommodate the then nascent process of microwave heating; however, FCC annual reports of that time suggest that much preparation was done ahead of these presentations.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Radio frequencies in the ISM bands have been used for communication purposes, although such devices may experience interference from non-communication sources.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] In the U.S., the FCC first made unlicensed spread spectrum available in the ISM bands in rules adopted on May 9, 1985.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The FCC action was proposed by Michael Marcus of the FCC staff in 1980 and the subsequent regulatory action took five more years.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] It was part of a broader proposal to allow civil use of spread spectrum technology and was opposed at the time by mainstream equipment manufacturers and many radio system operators.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Many other countries later developed similar regulations, enabling use of this technology.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The original ISM specifications envisioned that the bands would be used primarily for noncommunication purposes, such as heating.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The bands are still widely used for these purposes.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] For many people, the most commonly encountered ISM device is the home microwave oven operating at 2.45 GHz which uses microwaves to cook food.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Industrial heating is another big application area; such as induction heating, microwave heat treating, plastic softening, and plastic welding processes.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] In medical settings, shortwave and microwave diathermy machines use radio waves in the ISM bands to apply deep heating to the body for relaxation and healing.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] More recently hyperthermia therapy uses microwaves to heat tissue to kill cancer cells.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] These are sometimes called "non ISM" uses since they do not fall under the originally envisioned "industrial", "scientific", and "medical" application areas.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] One of the largest applications has been wireless networking (Wi-Fi).
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The IEEE 802.11ah wireless networking protocols, the standards on which almost all wireless systems are based, use the ISM bands.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Virtually all laptops, tablet computers, computer printers and cellphones now have 802.11 wireless modems using the 2.4 and 5.7 GHz ISM bands.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Bluetooth is another networking technology using the 2.4 GHz band, which can be problematic given the probability of interference.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Near-field communication (NFC) devices such as proximity cards and contactless smart cards use the lower-frequency 13 and 27 MHz ISM bands.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Multiple international LoRa standards use ISM bands for low-power, long-range, low-rate data transmission.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Some electrodeless lamp designs are ISM devices, which use RF emissions to excite fluorescent tubes.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Sulfur lamps are commercially available plasma lamps, which use 2.45 GHz magnetrons to heat sulfur into a brightly glowing plasma.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Long-distance wireless power systems have been proposed and experimented with which would use high-power transmitters and rectennas, in lieu of overhead transmission lines and underground cables, to send power to remote locations.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] NASA has studied using microwave power transmission on 2.45 GHz to send energy collected by solar power satellites back to the ground.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Also in space applications, a helicon double-layer ion thruster is a prototype spacecraft propulsion engine which uses a 13.56 MHz transmission to break down and heat gas into plasma.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] In recent years ISM bands have also been shared with (non-ISM) license-free error-tolerant communications applications such as wireless sensor networks in the 915 MHz and 2.450 GHz bands, as well as wireless LANs and cordless phones in the 915 MHz, 2.450 GHz, and 5.800 GHz bands.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Because unlicensed devices are required to be tolerant of ISM emissions in these bands, unlicensed low-power users are generally able to operate in these bands without causing problems for ISM users.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] ISM equipment does not necessarily include a radio receiver in the ISM band (e.g. a microwave oven does not have a receiver).
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] In the United States, according to 47 CFR Part 15.5, low power communication devices must accept interference from licensed users of that frequency band, and the Part 15 device must not cause interference to licensed users.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Note that the 915 MHz band should not be used in countries outside Region 2, except those that specifically allow it, such as Australia (915 MHz to 928 MHz) and Israel, especially those that use the GSM-900 band for cellphones.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] The ISM bands are also widely used for radio-frequency identification (RFID) applications with the most commonly used band being the 13.56 MHz band used by systems compliant with ISO/IEC 14443 including those used by biometric passports and contactless smart cards.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] In Europe, the use of the ISM band is covered by Short Range Device regulations issued by European Commission, based on technical recommendations by CEPT and standards by ETSI.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] In most of Europe, LPD433 band is allowed for license-free voice communication in addition to PMR446.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Wireless LANs and cordless phones can also use bands other than those shared with ISM, but such uses require approval on a country by country basis.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] DECT phones use allocated spectrum outside the ISM bands that differs in Europe and North America.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Ultra-wideband LANs require more spectrum than the ISM bands can provide, so the relevant standards such as IEEE 802.15.4a are designed to make use of spectrum outside the ISM bands.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Despite the fact that these additional bands are outside the official ITU-R ISM bands, because they are used for the same types of low power personal communications, they are sometimes incorrectly referred to as ISM bands as well.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Several brands of radio control equipment use the 2.4 GHz band range for low power remote control of toys, from gas powered cars to miniature aircraft.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Worldwide Digital Cordless Telecommunications or WDCT is a technology that uses the 2.4 GHz radio spectrum.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Google's Project Loon used ISM bands (specifically 2.4 and 5.8 GHz bands) for balloon-to-balloon and balloon-to-ground communications.
[src:sigfox/ism-radio-band] Pursuant to 47 CFR Part 97 some ISM bands are used by licensed amateur radio operators for communication – including amateur television.
[src:sigfox/low-power-wide-area-network] A **low-power, wide-area network** (**LPWAN** or **LPWA network**) is a type of wireless telecommunication wide area network designed to allow long-range communication at a low bit rate between IoT devices, such as sensors operated on a battery.
[src:sigfox/low-power-wide-area-network] Low power, low bit rate, and intended use distinguish this type of network from a wireless WAN that is designed to connect users or businesses, and carry more data, using more power.
[src:sigfox/low-power-wide-area-network] The LPWAN data rate ranges from 0.3 kbit/s to 50 kbit/s per channel.
[src:sigfox/low-power-wide-area-network] A LPWAN may be used to create a private wireless sensor network, but may also be a service or infrastructure offered by a third party, allowing the owners of sensors to deploy them in the field without investing in gateway technology.
[src:sigfox/low-power-wide-area-network] **Power:** LPWAN manufacturers claim years to decades of usable life from built-in batteries, but real-world application tests have not confirmed this.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] More recent machine to machine communication has changed into a system of networks that transmits data to personal appliances.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The expansion of IP networks has made M2M communication quicker and easier while using less power, and it is a component of the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] These networks also allow new business opportunities for consumers and suppliers.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Wired communication machines have been using signaling to exchange information since the early 20th century.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Machine to machine has taken more sophisticated forms since the advent of computer networking automation and predates cellular communication.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] It has been utilized in applications such as telemetry, industrial, automation, and SCADA.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Machine to machine devices that combined telephony and computing were first conceptualized by Theodore Paraskevakos while working on his Caller ID system in 1968, later patented in the U.S. in 1973.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] This system, similar but distinct from the panel call indicator of the 1920s and automatic number identification of the 1940s, which communicated telephone numbers to machines, was the predecessor to what is now caller ID, which communicates numbers to people.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] After several attempts and experiments, he realized that in order for the telephone to be able to read the caller's telephone number, it must possess intelligence so he developed the method in which the caller's number is transmitted to the called receiver's device.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] His portable transmitter and receiver were reduced to practice in 1971 in a Boeing facility in Huntsville, Alabama, representing the world's first working prototypes of caller identification devices (shown at right).
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] They were installed at Peoples' Telephone Company in Leesburg, Alabama and in Athens, Greece where they were demonstrated to several telephone companies with great success.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] This method was the basis for modern-day Caller ID technology.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] He was also the first to introduce the concepts of intelligence, data processing and visual display screens into telephones which gave rise to the smartphone.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In 1977, Paraskevakos started Metretek, Inc. in Melbourne, Florida to conduct commercial automatic meter reading and load management for electrical services which led to the "smart grid" and "smart meter".
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] To achieve mass appeal, Paraskevakos sought to reduce the size of the transmitter and the time of transmission through telephone lines by creating a single chip processing and transmission method.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Motorola was contracted in 1978 to develop and produce the single chip, but the chip was too large for Motorola's capabilities at that time.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] As a result, it became two separate chips (shown at right).
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] While cellular is becoming more common, many machines still use landlines (POTS, DSL, cable) to connect to the IP network.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The first M1 module was used for early point of sale (POS) terminals, in vehicle **telematics**, remote monitoring and **track and trace** applications.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Machine to machine technology was first embraced by early implementers such as GM and Hughes Electronics Corporation who realized the benefits and future potential of the technology.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] By 1997, machine to machine wireless technology became more prevalent and sophisticated as ruggedized modules were developed and launched for the specific needs of different vertical markets such as automotive telematics.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Another example of an early use is OnStar's **vehicle tracking system**.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The hardware components of a machine to machine network are manufactured by a few key players.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In 1998, Quake Global started designing and manufacturing machine to machine satellite and terrestrial modems.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Initially relying heavily on the Orbcomm network for its satellite communication services, Quake Global expanded its telecommunication product offerings by engaging both satellite and terrestrial networks, which gave Quake Global an edge in offering network-neutral products.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In 2004, Digi International began producing wireless gateways and routers.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Shortly after in 2006, Digi purchased Max Stream, the manufacturer of XBee radios.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] These hardware components allowed users to connect machines no matter how remote their location.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Since then, Digi has partnered with several companies to connect hundreds of thousands of devices around the world.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In 2004, Christopher Lowery, a UK telecoms entrepreneur, founded Wyless Group, one of the first Mobile Virtual Network Operators (MVNO) in the M2M space.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Operations began in the UK and Lowery published several patents introducing new features in data protection & management, including Fixed IP Addressing combined with Platform Managed Connectivity over VPNs.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The company expanded to the US in 2008 and became T-Mobile's largest partners on both sides of the Atlantic.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In 2006, Machine-to-Machine Intelligence (M2Mi) Corp started work with NASA to develop automated machine to machine intelligence.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Automated machine to machine intelligence enables a wide variety of mechanisms including wired or wireless tools, sensors, devices, server computers, robots, spacecraft and grid systems to communicate and exchange information efficiently.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In 2009, AT&T and Jasper Technologies, Inc. entered into an agreement to support the creation of machine to machine devices jointly.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] They have stated that they will be trying to drive further connectivity between consumer electronics and machine to machine wireless networks, which would create a boost in speed and overall power of such devices.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] 2009 also saw the introduction of real-time management of GSM and CDMA network services for machine to machine applications with the launch of the PRiSMPro™ Platform from machine to machine network provider KORE Telematics.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The platform focused on making multi-network management a critical component for efficiency improvements and cost-savings in machine to machine device and network usage.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Also in 2009, Wyless Group introduced PORTHOS™, its multi-operator, multi-application, device agnostic Open Data Management Platform.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The company introduced a new industry definition, Global Network Enabler, comprising customer-facing platform management of networks, devices and applications.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Also in 2009, the Norwegian incumbent Telenor concluded ten years of machine to machine research by setting up two entities serving the upper (services) and lower (connectivity) parts of the value-chain.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Telenor Connexion in Sweden draws on Vodafone's former research capabilities in subsidiary Europolitan and is in Europe's market for services across such typical markets as logistics, **fleet management**, car safety, healthcare, and smart metering of electricity consumption.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Telenor Objects has a similar role supplying connectivity to machine to machine networks across Europe.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In the UK, Business MVNO Abica, commenced trials with Telehealth and Telecare applications which required secure data transit via Private APN and HSPA+/4G LTE connectivity with static IP address.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In early 2010 in the U.S., AT&T, KPN, Rogers, Telcel / America Movil and Jasper Technologies, Inc. began to work together in the creation of a machine to machine site, which will serve as a hub for developers in the field of machine to machine communication electronics.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In January 2011, Aeris Communications, Inc. announced that it is providing machine to machine telematics services for Hyundai Motor Corporation.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Partnerships like these make it easier, faster and more cost-efficient for businesses to use machine to machine.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In June 2010, mobile messaging operator Tyntec announced the availability of its high-reliability SMS services for M2M applications.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Later that year, KORE acquired Australia-based Mach Communications Pty Ltd. in response to increased M2M demand within Asia-Pacific markets.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In April 2011, Ericsson acquired Telenor Connexion's machine to machine platform, in an effort to get more technology and know-how in the growing sector.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In August 2011, Ericsson announced that they have successfully completed the asset purchase agreement to acquire Telenor Connexion's (machine to machine) technology platform.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] According to the independent wireless analyst firm Berg Insight, the number of cellular network connections worldwide used for machine to machine communication was 47.7 million in 2008.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The company forecasts that the number of machine to machine connections will grow to 187 million by 2014.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] A research study from the E-Plus Group shows that in 2010 2.3 million machine to machine smart cards will be in the German market.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] According to the study, this figure will rise in 2013 to over 5 million smart cards.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The main growth driver is segment "tracking and tracing" with an expected average growth rate of 30 percent.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The fastest growing M2M segment in Germany, with an average annual growth of 47 percent, will be the consumer electronics segment.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In April 2013, OASIS MQTT standards group is formed with the goal of working on a lightweight publish/subscribe reliable messaging transport protocol suitable for communication in M2M/IoT contexts.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] IBM and StormMQ chair this standards group and Machine-to-Machine Intelligence (M2Mi) Corp is the secretary.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In May 2014, the committee published the MQTT and NIST Cybersecurity Framework Version 1.0 committee note to provide guidance for organizations wishing to deploy MQTT in a way consistent with the NIST Framework for Improving Critical Infrastructure Cybersecurity.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In May 2013, machine to machine network service providers KORE Telematics, Oracle, Deutsche Telekom, Digi International, Orbcomm and Telit formed the International Machine to Machine Council (IMC).
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The first trade organization to service the entire machine to machine ecosystem, the IMC aims at making machine to machine ubiquitous by helping companies install and manage the communication between machines.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Wireless networks that are all interconnected can serve to improve production and efficiency in various areas, including machinery that works on building cars and on letting the developers of products know when certain products need to be taken in for maintenance and for what reason.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Such information serves to streamline products that consumers buy and works to keep them all working at highest efficiency.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Another application is to use wireless technology to monitor systems, such as utility meters.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] This would allow the owner of the meter to know if certain elements have been tampered with, which serves as a quality method to stop fraud.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In Quebec, Rogers will connect Hydro Quebec's central system with up to 600 Smart Meter collectors, which aggregate data relayed from the province's 3.8-million Smart Meters.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In the UK, Telefónica won on a €1.78 billion ($2.4 billion) smart-meter contract to provide connectivity services over a period of 15 years in the central and southern regions of the country.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The contract is the industry's biggest deal yet.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Some companies, such as M-kopa in Kenya, are using M2M to enforce a payment plan, by turning off its customers' solar devices remotely for non-payment.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] "Our loan officer is that SIM card in the device that can shut it off remotely," says Chad Larson, M-Kopa's finance director and its third co-founder, when describing the technology.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] A third application is to use wireless networks to update digital billboards.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] This allows advertisers to display different messages based on time of day or day-of-week, and allows quick global changes for messages, such as pricing changes for gasoline.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The industrial machine to machine market is undergoing a fast transformation as enterprises are increasingly realizing the value of connecting geographically dispersed people, devices, sensors and machines to corporate networks.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Today, industries such as oil and gas, precision agriculture, military, government, smart cities/municipalities, manufacturing, and public utilities, among others, utilize machine to machine technologies for a myriad of applications.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Many companies have enabled complex and efficient data networking technologies to provide capabilities such as high-speed data transmission, mobile mesh networking, and 3G/4G cellular backhaul.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Machine to machine wireless networks can serve to improve the production and efficiency of machines, to enhance the reliability and safety of complex systems, and to promote the life-cycle management for key assets and products.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The application of intelligent analysis tools and Device-to-Business (D2B) TM informatics platform form the basis of e-maintenance machine network that can lead to near-zero downtime performance of machines and systems.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The e-maintenance machine network provides integration between the factory floor system and e-business system, and thus enables the real time decision making in terms of near-zero downtime, reducing uncertainties and improved system performance.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In addition, with the help of highly interconnected machine networks and advance intelligent analysis tools, several novel maintenance types are made possible nowadays.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] For instance, the distant maintenance without dispatching engineers on-site, the online maintenance without shutting down the operating machines or systems, and the predictive maintenance before a machine failure become catastrophic.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] All these benefits of e-maintenance machine network add up improve the maintenance efficiency and transparency significantly.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] As described in, The framework of e-maintenance machine network consists of sensors, data acquisition system, communication network, analytic agents, decision-making support knowledge base, information synchronization interface and e-business system for decision making.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Initially, the sensors, controllers and operators with data acquisition are used to collect the raw data from equipment and send it out to Data Transformation Layer automatically via internet or intranet.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The Data Transform Layer then employs signal processing tools and feature extraction methods to convert the raw data into useful information.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] This converted information often carries rich information about the reliability and availability of machines or system and is more agreeable for intelligent analysis tools to perform subsequent process.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The Synchronization Module and Intelligent Tools comprise the major processing power of the e-maintenance machine network and provide optimization, prediction, clustering, classification, bench-marking and so on.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The results from this module can then be synchronized and shared with the e-business system on for decision making.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In real application, the synchronization module will provide connection with other departments at the decision making level, like enterprise resource planning (ERP), customer relation management (CRM) and supply chain management (SCM).
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Another application of machine to machine network is in the health management for a fleet of similar machines using clustering approach.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] This method was introduced to address the challenge of developing fault detection models for applications with non-stationary operating regimes or with incomplete data.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The overall methodology consists of two stages: 1) Fleet Clustering to group similar machines for sound comparison; 2) Local Cluster Fault Detection to evaluate the similarity of individual machines to the fleet features.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The purpose of fleet clustering is to aggregate working units with similar configurations or working conditions into a group for sound comparison and subsequently create local fault detection models when global models cannot be established.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Within the framework of peer to peer comparison methodology, the machine to machine network is crucial to ensure the instantaneous information share between different working units and thus form the basis of fleet level health management technology.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The fleet level health management using clustering approach was patented for its application in wind turbine health monitoring after validated in a wind turbine fleet of three distributed wind farms.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Different with other industrial devices with fixed or static regimes, wind turbine's operating condition is greatly dictated by wind speed and other ambient factors.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Even though the multi-modeling methodology can be applicable in this scenario, the number of wind turbines in a wind farm is almost infinite and may not present itself as a practical solution.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Instead, by leveraging on data generated from other similar turbines in the network, this problem can be properly solved and local fault detection models can be effective built.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] The results of wind turbine fleet level health management reported in demonstrated the effectiveness of applying a cluster-based fault detection methodology in the wind turbine networks.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Fault detection for a horde of industrial robots experiences similar difficulties as lack of fault detection models and dynamic operating condition.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Industrial robots are crucial in automotive manufacturing and perform different tasks as welding, material handling, painting, etc.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] In this scenario, robotic maintenance becomes critical to ensure continuous production and avoid downtime.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Historically, the fault detection models for all the industrial robots are trained similarly.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Critical model parameters like training samples, components, and alarming limits are set the same for all the units regardless of their different functionalities.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] Even though these identical fault detection models can effectively identify faults sometimes, numerous false alarms discourage users from trusting the reliability of the system.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] However, within a machine network, industrial robots with similar tasks or working regimes can be group together; the abnormal units in a cluster can then be prioritized for maintenance via training based or instantaneous comparison.
[src:sigfox/machine-to-machine] This peer to peer comparison methodology inside a machine network could improve the fault detection accuracy significantly.
[src:sigfox/narrowband] In radio communications, a narrowband channel is a channel in which the bandwidth of the message does not significantly exceed the channel's coherence bandwidth.
[src:sigfox/narrowband] In the study of wired channels, *narrowband* implies that the channel under consideration is sufficiently narrow that its frequency response can be considered flat.
[src:sigfox/narrowband] The message bandwidth will therefore be less than the coherence bandwidth of the channel.
[src:sigfox/narrowband] That is, no channel has perfectly flat fading, but the analysis of many aspects of wireless systems is greatly simplified if flat fading can be assumed.
[src:sigfox/narrowband] Two-Way Radio Narrowbanding refers to a U.S.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] Sigfox is based in Labège near Toulouse, France, and once had over 375 employees in Madrid, San Francisco, Sydney and Paris.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] The former Sigfox entity had raised more than $300 million from investors that included Salesforce, Intel, Samsung, NTT, SK Telecom, energy groups Total and Air Liquide.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] In November 2016 Sigfox was valued at around €600 million.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] In January 2022 it filed for bankruptcy.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] In April 2022 Singapore-based IoT company UnaBiz acquired the Sigfox 0G technology and its French network operations for a reported €25 million ($27m).
[src:sigfox/sigfox] As of December 2024, the Sigfox 0G network managed by UnaBiz supports over 14 million active connected devices worldwide.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] Following the acquisition, national operators that owned their own infrastructure continued service independently.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] In Mexico, the network operator reported processing over 8 million messages daily from more than 500,000 endpoints without service interruption during or after the insolvency process.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] Sigfox employs differential binary phase-shift keying (DBPSK) and Gaussian frequency shift keying (GFSK) over the Short-range device band of 868 MHz in Europe, and the Industrial, Scientific and Medical radio band of 902 MHz in the US.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] It utilizes a wide-reaching signal that passes freely through solid objects, called "Ultra Narrowband" and requires little energy, being termed a "low-power wide-area network" (LPWAN).
[src:sigfox/sigfox] The network is based on one-hop star topology.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] The signal can also be used to easily cover large areas and to reach underground objects.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] As of December 2024, the Sigfox 0G global network has covered a total of 5.8 million square kilometers in a total of 75 countries with 1.3 billion of the world population reached.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] The Sigfox 0G technology is supported by a number of firms in the LPWAN industry such as NXP Semiconductors, Holtek, ST Microelectronics, Semtech and Silicon Labs.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] The ISM radio bands support limited bidirectional communication.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] The existing standard for Sigfox communications supports up to 140 uplink messages a day, each of which can carry a payload of 12 octets (Byte) at a data rate of up to 100 bits per second, and/or 600bit/s in some regions.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] Upon acquisition, UnaBiz released the Sigfox device library code for connected objects to the public and IoT development community to drive technology interoperability and the unification of LPWANs in the IoT industry.
[src:sigfox/sigfox] The developer community can now visit the 0G technology's Github page and Build to access the new device library codes and related documentation.
